    {
      "id": "Z1cKlxoj_Ezh8M6VAOv9y",
      "type": "text",
      "x": 302.399292442076,
      "y": 455.8531704633392,
      "width": 1207.8466796875,
      "height": 2783.8696555079346,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1971c2",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 2,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "a0",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 186360330,
      "version": 3868,
      "versionNonce": 1821571293,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775315536786,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "Functional Requirements:\n    QR payment from sender to receiver on scan\n    Transaction History\n    Add balance to e-wallet from 3rd party banking api\n\n\nNon-Functional Requirements:\n    Fault tolerant\n    Highly consistent\n    Based on CAP theorem, this system would follow C&P \n    Idempotency\n    Low latency\n    Failure Handling\n    Highly scalable\n\n\nDB Choice:\n    We need ACID properties, so SQL db (eg. PostgreSQL).  (PostgresSQL v/s MySQL??)\n    But nowadays NOSQL DB also provides ACID gurantees with high scalability and lpw latency\n    (eg; DynamoDB which provides transactional read and write??) \n    \n    Ledger DB or ledger table.\n\n\nTraffic Calculation:\n    What estimation? \n      \n \n        Total users=10M\n        Daily active users=6M\n        Daily total transactions=5 transactions per user= 5*6M=30M transactions daily\n        Total transactions per second=(12M read request daily+18M write request daily)/80,000\n                                              =(120/8*10^1)=150 read request per sec \n                                              =(180/8*10)=240 write request per sec\n        Peak Tps(4x)\n            Total request/sec=400\n            Total peak TPS=1600\n            \n        On Avg. each server handles lets say 400 request so we need 1600/400=4-5 servers.\n\n        Peak DB transaction = total write tps*(4-5 avg db round trip)\n                                   =1000 write transaction on db per sec.\n    \n\n        (Partioning vs Sharding?? Consistent Hashing??)\n\n\nAPI design\n GET \n    /v1/users/{userId}/balance\n    /v1/users/{userId]/transactions\n\nPOST\n    /v1/users/topup\n    /v1/users/transfer\n\n\nUser Login:\n    Authentication on auth server, and access token with refresh token is stord in HTTP only secure cookies.\n    Which is sent with subsequent request.\n\n\nNumber of microservices:\n    I'll take 3 (1 for get request, 1 for post request, 1 for user login)\n\nSchema Design\n\n    UUID is incremental uuid. Index is faster on incremental uuid.\n    \n        Wallet {\n            UUID walletId notNull    \n            UUID userId notNull (FK)\n            Double balance notNULL\n        }\n    \n        User {\n            UUID userId notNULL\n            string name notNULL\n        }\n        \n        TransactionsLedger {\n            UUID txnID notNULL (generated by server)\n            UUID bankReferenceID (sent by response from 3rd party banking api)\n            String idempotencyKey notNULL (generated by client)\n            UUID UserId notNULL\n            UUID walletId notNULL\n            String status (ENUM->INITIATED, PROCESSING, SUCCESS, FAILED)\n            Double amount notNULL (-negative for sent, +for received)\n            OffsetDateTime timestamp;\n        }\n\nDesign:\n    \n    \n\n\n                                                      \n    \n   ",
      "fontSize": 22.495916408144925,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "Functional Requirements:\n    QR payment from sender to receiver on scan\n    Transaction History\n    Add balance to e-wallet from 3rd party banking api\n\n\nNon-Functional Requirements:\n    Fault tolerant\n    Highly consistent\n    Based on CAP theorem, this system would follow C&P \n    Idempotency\n    Low latency\n    Failure Handling\n    Highly scalable\n\n\nDB Choice:\n    We need ACID properties, so SQL db (eg. PostgreSQL).  (PostgresSQL v/s MySQL??)\n    But nowadays NOSQL DB also provides ACID gurantees with high scalability and lpw latency\n    (eg; DynamoDB which provides transactional read and write??) \n    \n    Ledger DB or ledger table.\n\n\nTraffic Calculation:\n    What estimation? \n      \n \n        Total users=10M\n        Daily active users=6M\n        Daily total transactions=5 transactions per user= 5*6M=30M transactions daily\n        Total transactions per second=(12M read request daily+18M write request daily)/80,000\n                                              =(120/8*10^1)=150 read request per sec \n                                              =(180/8*10)=240 write request per sec\n        Peak Tps(4x)\n            Total request/sec=400\n            Total peak TPS=1600\n            \n        On Avg. each server handles lets say 400 request so we need 1600/400=4-5 servers.\n\n        Peak DB transaction = total write tps*(4-5 avg db round trip)\n                                   =1000 write transaction on db per sec.\n    \n\n        (Partioning vs Sharding?? Consistent Hashing??)\n\n\nAPI design\n GET \n    /v1/users/{userId}/balance\n    /v1/users/{userId]/transactions\n\nPOST\n    /v1/users/topup\n    /v1/users/transfer\n\n\nUser Login:\n    Authentication on auth server, and access token with refresh token is stord in HTTP only secure cookies.\n    Which is sent with subsequent request.\n\n\nNumber of microservices:\n    I'll take 3 (1 for get request, 1 for post request, 1 for user login)\n\nSchema Design\n\n    UUID is incremental uuid. Index is faster on incremental uuid.\n    \n        Wallet {\n            UUID walletId notNull    \n            UUID userId notNull (FK)\n            Double balance notNULL\n        }\n    \n        User {\n            UUID userId notNULL\n            string name notNULL\n        }\n        \n        TransactionsLedger {\n            UUID txnID notNULL (generated by server)\n            UUID bankReferenceID (sent by response from 3rd party banking api)\n            String idempotencyKey notNULL (generated by client)\n            UUID UserId notNULL\n            UUID walletId notNULL\n            String status (ENUM->INITIATED, PROCESSING, SUCCESS, FAILED)\n            Double amount notNULL (-negative for sent, +for received)\n            OffsetDateTime timestamp;\n        }\n\nDesign:\n    \n    \n\n\n                                                      \n    \n   ",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
