      "text": "1) Check Balance, hits cache.\n2) Cache not found, Hits DB, and updates cache to read balance.\n3) Get Transaction History, can read from read-replicas.\n4) Add Balance event goes to Kafka partition which is \ndecided by hash on userId(helps in controlling concurrency)\n5) Transaction processor reads the event and call the Bank \napi to add money to wallet. \n6) The request is sent to bank server.\n7 & 8) The status response is then received via SSE events and \nwallet, transaction table and ledger is updated in a single transaction.\n9) Now transfer money with balance update and ledger entry transactions is done \nall at once or all fail. It brings strong consistency to our system and atomicity.\n\n\nNotable points:\n1) Leader DB is sharded by shard_id which in my case would be walletId. \nTo scale writes operations.\n2) Cache invalidation in redis, for every new walletID transaction update and new entry is created.\n3) Idempotency check by idempotency_key by WalletDetail Service and return the same response as before\n    on re-request.\n4) DLQ for any addBalance event fails to process, max_retries is done from this dlq and if it still fails is further notified \n    for inspection.\n5) Transactions status can be related to state machine -> INITIATED->INPROGRESS->SUCCESS/FAILED\n6) Ledger Table is treated as source of truth. And reconcilation job is run based on any discrepancy.\n7) Partition happends, db nodes goes out of sync. Critical Request are always meant to be served from leader db, in \ncase it is not available: fail or retry.  Hence availability is compromised. \n",
      "fontSize": 27.88588357072292,
      "fontFamily": 5,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "1) Check Balance, hits cache.\n2) Cache not found, Hits DB, and updates cache to read balance.\n3) Get Transaction History, can read from read-replicas.\n4) Add Balance event goes to Kafka partition which is \ndecided by hash on userId(helps in controlling concurrency)\n5) Transaction processor reads the event and call the Bank \napi to add money to wallet. \n6) The request is sent to bank server.\n7 & 8) The status response is then received via SSE events and \nwallet, transaction table and ledger is updated in a single transaction.\n9) Now transfer money with balance update and ledger entry transactions is done \nall at once or all fail. It brings strong consistency to our system and atomicity.\n\n\nNotable points:\n1) Leader DB is sharded by shard_id which in my case would be walletId. \nTo scale writes operations.\n2) Cache invalidation in redis, for every new walletID transaction update and new entry is created.\n3) Idempotency check by idempotency_key by WalletDetail Service and return the same response as before\n    on re-request.\n4) DLQ for any addBalance event fails to process, max_retries is done from this dlq and if it still fails is further notified \n    for inspection.\n5) Transactions status can be related to state machine -> INITIATED->INPROGRESS->SUCCESS/FAILED\n6) Ledger Table is treated as source of truth. And reconcilation job is run based on any discrepancy.\n7) Partition happends, db nodes goes out of sync. Critical Request are always meant to be served from leader db, in \ncase it is not available: fail or retry.  Hence availability is compromised. \n",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
